.prev,\n      [id]: result.success\n        ? { type: \"success\", message: \"Sent\" }\n        : { type: \"error\", message: result.error ?? \"Error\" },\n    }));\n  }\n\n  const buttons: Array<{\n    id: string;\n    label: string;\n    getPayload: () => EventPayload;\n  }> = [\n    {\n      id: \"anon-page-view\",\n      label: \"Anonymous Page View\",\n      getPayload: () => ({\n        event_name: \"Page Viewed\",\n        device_id: generateId(),\n        properties: { page: \"/home\" },\n      }),\n    },\n    {\n      id: \"button-click\",\n      label: \"Button Click\",\n      getPayload: () => ({\n        event_name: \"Button Clicked\",\n        device_id: lastDeviceId ?? generateId(),\n        properties: { button_name: \"Get Started\" },\n      }),\n    },\n    {\n      id: \"identify-user\",\n      label: \"Identify User\",\n      getPayload: () => ({\n        event_name: \"Identify\",\n        device_id: lastDeviceId ?? generateId(),\n        user_id: TEST_USER_ID,\n      }),\n    },\n    {\n      id: \"purchase\",\n      label: \"Purchase\",\n      getPayload: () => ({\n        event_name: \"Purchase Completed\",\n        user_id: TEST_USER_ID,\n        properties: { amount: 49.99, currency: \"USD\" },\n      }),\n    },\n    {\n      id: \"signup\",\n      label: \"Signup\",\n      getPayload: () => ({\n        event_name: \"Signup Completed\",\n        device_id: generateId(),\n        user_id: `user-${generateId()}@example.com`,\n      }),\n    },\n  ];\n\n  return (\n    <Box data-testid=\"quick-fire-buttons\">\n      <Stack spacing={1}>\n        {buttons.map(({ id, label, getPayload }) => (\n          <Box key={id}>\n            <Button\n              variant=\"outlined\"\n              size=\"small\"\n              disabled={loadingButton === id}\n              onClick={() => void fire(id, getPayload)}\n              fullWidth\n            >\n              {label}\n            </Button>\n            {feedback[id] != null && (\n              <Typography\n                variant=\"caption\"\n                color={feedback[id]?.type === \"success\" ? \"success.main\" : \"error.main\"}\n                sx={{ display: \"block\", mt: 0.25 }}\n              >\n                {feedback[id]?.type === \"success\"\n                  ? \"Sent\"\n                  : `Error: ${feedback[id]?.message}`}\n              </Typography>\n            )}\n          </Box>\n        ))}\n      </Stack>\n    </Box>\n  );\n}\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JicY6oc5xQGtRZMhcyyKVC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's an issue: the `QuickFireButtons` component uses `useEventSender` internally and the `lastDeviceId` from the hook. When I call `fire()` with the `getPayload` function, `getPayload` captures `lastDeviceId` at definition time (via closure). But `buttons` is re-created on each render, so `lastDeviceId` in the closure would always be fresh.\n\nWait, actually there might be a stale closure issue. The `buttons` array is defined inside the component and references `lastDeviceId` from the component's render scope. Each time the component re-renders (after `setLastDeviceId` is called), the `buttons` array is recreated with the updated `lastDeviceId`. \n\nSo the `getPayload` functions inside `buttons` close over the current `lastDeviceId` at render time, which means when a button is clicked, it uses whatever `lastDeviceId` was set in the most recent render. This should work correctly since clicking \"Anonymous Page View\" triggers a state update and re-render before the next button click happens. But I'm wondering if the test might have a timing issue with the fetch call after that first click.\n\nThe flow is: clicking the button fires the event, which calls `sendEvent` with a new device_id, the mock fetch resolves immediately, then `setLastDeviceId` gets called and queues a re-render. The test waits for the fetch to be called, but I need to verify whether React has actually finished re-rendering with the updated `lastDeviceId` by that point, especially in React 18 where batching behavior might affect the timing. and concurrent mode, `waitFor` wraps each check in `act()`, which should flush all pending state updates. So by the time `waitFor` resolves, all React state updates should have been applied.\n\nActually, I'm not 100% sure about this. The `waitFor` polls until the condition is true. At the moment the condition becomes true (mockFetch called once), the state update might still be pending. But then `waitFor` wraps each check in `act`, which flushes state updates before checking...\n\nActually looking at the implementation of `waitFor` in @testing-library/react, it wraps each interval check in `act`. So when it checks `expect(mockFetch).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1)`, it first runs an `act` flush, which should commit any pending state updates.\n\nWait, the issue is different. `waitFor` polls repeatedly, wrapping each check in `act` to flush React updates. When I click the button, it synchronously starts the click handler which calls `sendEvent` asynchronously. The mocked fetch resolves immediately and triggers `setLastDeviceId`, and by the time `waitFor` runs its next `act` flush, that state update should be committed.\n\nI think the test will work because `waitFor` keeps polling with `act` flushes until the condition passes.\n\nThe key insight is that when `useEventSender.sendEvent` calls `setLastDeviceId`, it triggers a re-render of `QuickFireButtons` since the component uses that hook. So after the fetch resolves and the state updates, the component will have the new `lastDeviceId` value ready for the next interaction.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a mismatch in my \"Identify User\" button implementation. The spec describes it as an identity link operation, not a standard event, but I'm sending it as an \"Identify\" event with a device_id and user_id. I need to check what the actual payload structure should be based on the identity resolution algorithm. I need an event_name for the \"Identify User\" action since the spec requires it, so I'm using \"Identify\" as the event type. My test correctly validates that the device_id and user_id are being sent properly, which is what matters for the identity link functionality. The \"Purchase\" button selector should work fine since it's just matching the button label. I'm realizing there might be an issue with how the `device_id` flows through the test—when \"Anonymous Page View\" is clicked, `sendEvent` gets called with a generated `device_id`, and that should update `lastDeviceId` after the fetch completes, but `getPayload` creates a fresh device ID each time.\n\nLet me trace through the sequence: clicking \"Anonymous Page View\" generates a device ID and sends it, then the mock resolves and updates `lastDeviceId`. When \"Button Click\" fires next, it should use that same `lastDeviceId` instead of generating a new one, so both events end up with matching device IDs. That should work correctly.\n\nNow I'm looking at the `fire` function implementation...\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how the closures work here. The `buttons` array is defined with `getPayload` functions that capture `lastDeviceId`, but since `fire` is recreated on each render, I need to verify that when a click happens, it's using the most recent `lastDeviceId` value from the component's state at that moment.\n\nThe flow is: user clicks → `onClick` handler fires with the current `getPayload` from the latest render → `fire` executes with that `getPayload` → `getPayload()` returns the payload with the current `lastDeviceId`. This should work correctly as long as the component has already re-rendered with the updated `lastDeviceId` before the click happens.\n\nI think the implementation is sound, so I'll move forward with it.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the `CustomEventForm` component structure. It needs a collapsible container with a toggle button labeled to match the test selector, form fields for event name, device ID, user ID, timestamp, and a properties textarea, plus validation for JSON and feedback after submission. The toggle button should use \"custom event\" in its label, and the form fields need labels that match the aria-label patterns from the tests.\n\nFor the collapse behavior, I need to verify how MUI's `Collapse` component affects the accessibility tree—it uses `height: 0` and `overflow: hidden` rather than `display: none`, so I should test whether that actually removes elements from the accessibility tree or if I need a different approach to make the fields truly inaccessible when collapsed. So the elements might still be in the accessibility tree. Let me check—MUI's Collapse component uses CSS transitions and sets `height: 0` with `overflow: hidden` when closed, which means child elements might still be accessible. I could use the `unmountOnExit` prop to remove them from the DOM entirely, or just conditionally render them with `{open && <FormFields />}`. Since the test expects `queryByRole` to return null when collapsed, conditional rendering is the safest approach to ensure elements aren't in the DOM at all.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the button labels—the toggle button needs to say \"Custom Event\" and the submit button needs to say \"Send\" so they're clearly distinct. The test queries for them separately using `/custom event/i` and `/^send$/i`, so as long as my labels match those patterns, the test should find the right buttons.\n\nFor the properties field, I need to make sure the textarea has a proper accessible label with \"properties\" in it so `getByRole(\"textbox\", { name: /properties/i })` can find it.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the invalid JSON error display—the test expects to find text matching \"invalid json\" when the properties contain malformed JSON, so I'll need to show that error message conditionally.\n\nFor the toggle behavior, I should use conditional rendering instead of the Collapse component to avoid any accessibility issues with the test checking that form fields disappear when toggled closed.\n\nThe test verifies that after two clicks (opening then closing), the textbox is completely removed from the DOM, which conditional rendering handles perfectly. This approach also satisfies the collapsible form requirement.\n\nLet me start building the CustomEventForm component now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1294,"cache_read_input_tokens":96364,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1294,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"27b757f3-6d9d-4fd7-9868-cc1b8f1bb385","uuid":"39a385cb-b76f-4c39-87da-dbe5801a8767"}
